  "doc_id": "23986",
  "text": "Congenital talipes equinovarus can be diagnosed antenatally using ultrasound. There is a wide variation in the reported accuracy. A recent study found that the diagnosis of clubfoot by ultrasound had a positive predictive value of 83% with a false positive rate of 17%. [CITATION_1] All the inaccuracies concerned the diagnosis. No cases of a complex clubfoot (CTEV with other congenital abnormalities) were missed, but the authors stressed that sequential scans of the fetus with CTEV were essential as the complexity of the deformities changed in 25% of cases. A similar study by Mammen and Benson [CITATION_2] found the false-positive rate was higher for unilateral (29%) than for bilateral clubfoot (7%). They noted that associated anomalies were more frequent with bilateral (76%) than with unilateral clubfoot (55%). Bar Hava et al [CITATION_3] described a transient deformity in the early weeks of gestation resembling clubfoot which was attributed to late maturation or high flexibility of the foetal limb muscles at this stage. Scans at 20 to 24 weeks may be more reliable for the diagnosis than those taken earlier.",
